      "answer": "Vaccines work by stimulating the immune system to recognize and neutralize specific pathogens, which reduces disease incidence. They achieve this by introducing antigens\u2014such as mRNA encoding pathogen proteins, protein subunits, or inactivated or weakened pathogens\u2014which prompt the production of immunological memory cells and antibodies. \n\nThe antibody response is mediated by B cells that differentiate into plasma cells to secrete large quantities of immunoglobulin; long-lived plasma cells and memory B cells then contribute to sustained immunity. This acquired immunity allows the immune system to rapidly recognize and neutralize the corresponding pathogen during future exposure, typically before a clinically significant infection can be established.",
